ts seeking land settled in the 1970s. Manz describes these villagers' plight as their isolated, lush, but deceptive paradise became one of the centers of the war convulsing the entire country. After their village was viciously sacked in 1982, desperate survivors fled into the surrounding rain forest and eventually to Mexico, and some even further, to the United States, while others stayed behind and fell into the military's hands. With great insight and compassion, Manz follows their flight and eventual return to Santa María Tzejá, where they sought to rebuild their village and their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCivil-military relationsxGuatemalaxSanta María Tzejá. 0aCivil-military relationszGuatemalazSanta María Tzejá. 0aMassacresxGuatemalaxSanta María Tzejá. 0aMassacreszGuatemalazSanta María Tzejá. 0aPolitical violencexGuatemalaxSanta María Tzejá. 0aPolitical violencezGuatemalazSanta María Tzejá. 0aQuiché IndiansxCrimes againstxGuatemalaxSanta María Tzejá. 0aQuiché IndiansxCrimes againstzGuatemalazSanta María Tzejá. 0aQuiché IndiansxRelocationxMexico. 0aQuiché IndiansxRelocationzMexico. 0aReturn migrationxGuatemalaxSanta María Tzejá. 0aReturn migrationzGuatemalazSanta María Tzejá. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939325423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520939325.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles